Now I understand the bug. At line 650, `p += Whsize_hd(hd)` is wrong. It should be `p += wh`. In the pool, every slot occupies `wh = wsize_sizeclass[sz]` words. `Whsize_hd(hd)` returns `wosize + 1` which is the header+data size of the *object*, not the slot size. This causes the sweep to misalign when walking through blocks.

Let me apply the fix:

```json
{
  "analysis": "The bug is at line 650 of runtime/shared_heap.c. The line `p += Whsize_hd(hd)` should be `p += wh`. In the pool, each slot is `wh = wsize_sizeclass[sz]` words, not `wosize+1` words. The wosize in the header reflects the original object size, not the padded slot size. This misalignment causes the sweep to read garbage headers and corrupt memory, leading to the segfault during bootstrap.",
  "plan": "Fix the bug, clean the build, and rebuild. Then run the basic testsuite.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "sed -i 's/^      p += Whsize_hd(hd);$/      p += wh;/' runtime/shared_heap.c\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "grep -n 'p += wh;' runtime/shared_heap.c | head -5\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "awk 'NR>=645 && NR<=655' runtime/shared_heap.c\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
